Step 2: Key Attrition Factors (Visuals):

Attrition by Department (Stacked Bar Chart):
Visual Type: Stacked Bar Chart
Axis (Y-Axis): Department
Values (X-Axis): Attrition Count (measure)
Legend: Attrition (Yes / No)

Project Note
Insight:      Department-wise         Attrition Rate
              Department	            Attrition Rate
              Sales	                  20.67% üî∫ Highest
              Human Resources        	19.05%
              Research & Development	13.75%
Designed a stacked bar chart to compare department-wise attrition distribution, enabling identification of high-turnover departments and workforce stability patterns.
The Sales department recorded the highest attrition rate (20.67%), exceeding the company average (16.19%), indicating a potential need for targeted retention and engagement strategies in Sales.
Sales Department (20.67%) has the highest attrition rate.

Impact of Overtime (Donut Chart):
Legend: OverTime
Values: Attrition Rate

Insight: 
OverTime - Yes: Employees who work overtime represent 74.72% of the total population in the dataset, and their attrition rate is 30.62%.
OverTime - No: Employees who do not work overtime represent 25.28% of the total population, and their attrition rate is 10.36%.

Attrition by Age Group (Clustered Column Chart):
Axis: AgeGroup (18-25, 26-35, etc.)
Values: Attrition Rate

Insight: Age Group of 18-25 are the highest Attrition rate of nearly 42%,  26-35 has 25.33% Attrition rate. 

Monthly Income vs. Attrition (Scatter Plot):
X-Axis: MonthlyIncome
Y-Axis: Age
Color: Attrition

Insight: The company‚Äôs attrition rate stands at 16.19%, with Sales showing the highest attrition (20.67%). Attrition is significantly higher among younger employees earning lower monthly income, highlighting compensation and early-career engagement as critical areas for retention strategy improvement.

3. Employee Satisfaction & Environment

Satisfaction Heatmap (Matrix):
Rows: JobRole
Columns: JobSatisfaction (Low to Very High)
Values: Attrition Rate
Formatting: Use Conditional Formatting (Red for high attrition, Green for low).

The Satisfaction Heatmap reveals a strong inverse relationship between job satisfaction and attrition rate. Attrition is highest among employees with low job satisfaction, particularly in Sales-related roles. Improving engagement, recognition, and career growth opportunities in these roles can significantly reduce turnover risk.

Tenure Analysis (Line Chart):
Axis: YearsAtCompany
Values: Attrition Count
Insight: Discover the "Peak Departure Year" (often year 1 or 2).

